name: Beak
desc: The tips of seagull's beaks are often slightly hooked, allowing them to grasp and tear apart their food easily. In addition, most seagulls have a red spot on their beaks!

name: Head
desc: Seagulls have special glands located above their eyes called salt glands. These glands help seagulls excrete excess salt from their bodies, as they often consume food from the sea, which can be high in salt content.

name: Tail
desc: A seagull's tail acts as a rudder, allowing them to make quick turns, hover, and navigate effectively while flying. This adaptation is crucial for their lifestyle of diving and scavenging.

name: Wing
desc: Seagulls, like many birds, have hollow bones in their wings. Wing spans range from  2-6 feet, depending on species. Click me to learn more about bird wings!

name: Feet
desc: Seagulls have webbed feet, just like many other water birds. Seagulls particularly though, have webbing that only goes about halfway up their toes. This adaptation helps them swim AND perch comfortably on solid ground.

name: Eyes
desc: Seagulls have a special adaptation that allows them to see ultraviolet light!

name: Eggs
desc: Seagull eggs are known for their speckled and camouflaging appearance, and usually come in clutches of about 3.

name: Keel
desc: Seagulls, like many other bird species, have a specialized chest bone called a "keel." The keel is a large, bony ridge along the center of the breastbone, and it serves as an anchor for the bird's powerful flight muscles. The development of a keel is essential for birds that are strong fliers!

name: Mantle
desc: Seagulls have a waterproof patch of feathers on their upper back called the mantle, coated with oil from a preen gland. This waterproofing helps them stay buoyant on water and protects their feathers for efficient flying and swimming.

name: Seagulls Diet
desc: Generally, they are omnivorous, meaning they eat both plants and animals. Seagulls will eat just about anything they can find, so their diet depends on what is available in their environment. In coastal areas, seagulls eat fish, crustaceans, mollusks, insects, and other marine life. They are also known to scavenge for food, meaning taking it from garbage cans, dumpsters, and stealing it from people on the beach.
